<h3>About Sir Francis Beaufort</h3>

<p><img alt=3D"Sir Francis Beaufort" data-entity-type=3D"file" height=3D"20=
0px" style=3D"padding:8px;" src=3D"https://www.rmets.org/sites/default/file=
s/2018-07/francis-beaufort-image.jpg" class=3D"align-left">The scale was de=
vised in 1805 by the Irish&nbsp;hydrographer&nbsp;Francis Beaufort&nbsp;(la=
ter&nbsp;Rear Admiral&nbsp;Sir Francis Beaufort), a&nbsp;Royal Navy&nbsp;of=
ficer while serving on&nbsp;HMS&nbsp;<em>Woolwich</em>. The scale that carr=
ies Beaufort's name had a long and complex evolution from the previous work=
 of others (including&nbsp;Daniel Defoe&nbsp;the century before) to when Be=
aufort was a Hydrographer of the Navy in the 1830s when it was adopted offi=
cially and first used during the voyage of&nbsp;HMS&nbsp;<em>Beagle</em>&nb=
sp;under Captain&nbsp;Robert FitzRoy, later to set up the first&nbsp;Meteor=
ological Office&nbsp;(Met Office) in Britain giving regular weather forecas=
ts.</p>

<p>In the early 19th century, naval officers made regular weather observati=
ons, but there was no standard scale, so they could be very subjective&nbsp=
;=E2=80=93 one man's "stiff breeze" might be another's "soft breeze". Beauf=
ort succeeded in standardising the scale.</p>

<h6>(From <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale">Wikipedi=
a</a>)</h6>

